'''Donyell Malen''' (born 19 January 1999) is a Dutch professional footballer who plays as a [[Winger (association football)|winger]] or [[Striker (association football)|striker]] for [[Serie A]] club [[AS Roma|Roma]] and the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands national team]].

Malen played youth football for [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] and [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] before joining [[PSV Eindhoven]] in 2017, playing for their youth side [[Jong PSV]] before graduating to the senior team. He joined [[Borussia Dortmund]] in 2021, spending four years at the club before joining Aston Villa.

Malen has played at every youth international level for the Netherlands from under-15 to senior.

==Club career==
===Early career===
Malen began his career with [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] in 2007. Despite a great deal of resistance coming from Ajax, in 2015 he left Ajax to join English club [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]. Malen joined up due to Arsenal being the side of his heroes [[Thierry Henry]] and [[Dennis Bergkamp]].<ref name=Donyell1 /><ref name="Feature2">{{cite web |title=Aanvaller Donyell Malen (17) en zijn moeder Mariska Manshanden |url=https://verhalen.volkskrant.nl/voetbalmoeders#2256 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170823165432/https://verhalen.volkskrant.nl/voetbalmoeders#2256 |archive-date=23 August 2017 |access-date=30 June 2017 |website=Volksrant.nl |language=nl}}</ref>

===Arsenal===
[[File:Donyell Malen2.jpg|thumb|left|Malen while featuring for Arsenal]]
Malen began playing for the youth teams of Arsenal in the [[Professional Development League|Youth Premier League]] together with the [[FA Youth Cup]], and the [[UEFA Youth League]] in the 2015–16 season. He began to display his impressive talent during his debut season for the Gunners.<ref name="Donyell">{{cite web |title=Donyell Malen: Profile |url=http://www.arsenal.com/academy/players/donyell-malen |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160513011941/http://www.arsenal.com/academy/players/donyell-malen |archive-date=13 May 2016 |access-date=10 May 2016 |publisher=Arsenal F.C.}}</ref> He scored in the [[FA Youth Cup]] quarter-final away to [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] which Arsenal won on penalties.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Turner |first1=Andy |title=Match report: Coventry City exit FA Youth Cup to Arsenal after dramatic penalty shoot-out |url=https://www.coventrytelegraph.net/sport/football/football-news/match-report-coventry-city-exit-10897694 |access-date=23 January 2021 |work=CoventryLive |date=15 February 2016}}</ref> Coming off the bench, he scored against [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in the semi-final of the [[2015–16 FA Youth Cup|2016 FA Youth Cup]] at the [[Emirates Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Manchester City pip Arsenal to FA Youth Cup final spot with 4–3 aggregate victory |url=https://www.thefa.com/news/2016/apr/04/arsenal-manchester-city-semi-final-second-leg-report-040416 |website=The FA |access-date=23 January 2021 |date=4 April 2016 |archive-date=30 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210130020316/https://www.thefa.com/news/2016/apr/04/arsenal-manchester-city-semi-final-second-leg-report-040416 |url-status=live }}</ref> and played 30 times during the season, scoring 14 goals.<ref name="Donyell" /> During the 2016–17 season, Malen was used a great deal on the wing,<ref name="Malen">{{cite web|title=Review: Leicester 0–3 Arsenal – Malen shines as Young Guns victorious|url=http://dailycannon.com/2017/01/review-leicester-0-3-arsenal-malen-shines-young-guns-victorious/|website=Daily Cannon.com|date=14 January 2017 |access-date=24 February 2017|archive-date=25 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170225130018/http://dailycannon.com/2017/01/review-leicester-0-3-arsenal-malen-shines-young-guns-victorious/|url-status=live}}</ref> and was included in the club's 2017–18 pre-season tour of Australia and China.<ref>{{cite web |title=Travelling squad for tour announced |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/travelling-squad-tour-announced |access-date=9 July 2017 |website=Arsenal.com}}</ref> He made his senior debut for Arsenal in a 2–0 win over [[Sydney F.C.|Sydney]] on 13 July.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2017/07/13/world/club-friendlies/sydney-fc/arsenal-fc/2233935/?ICID=HP_MS_46_01|title=SYDNEY VS. ARSENAL 0 – 2|publisher=Soccerway|access-date=21 February 2018|archive-date=23 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170823164110/http://int.soccerway.com/matches/2017/07/13/world/club-friendlies/sydney-fc/arsenal-fc/2233935/?ICID=HP_MS_46_01|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/report?gameId=489561|title=Alexandre Lacazette scores on Arsenal debut in friendly vs. Sydney FC|website=ESPN FC.com|access-date=13 July 2017|archive-date=14 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170714011403/http://www.espnfc.com/report?gameId=489561|url-status=live}}</ref>

===PSV Eindhoven===
Malen was sold by Arsenal to [[PSV Eindhoven]] in late August 2017.<ref name=Talksport>{{cite web|url= https://talksport.com/football/arsenal-fc-transfer-news-donyell-malen-returns-holland-join-psv-eindhoven-permanent-deal|title= Donyell Malen joins PSV Eindhoven|website= Talksport.com|access-date= 8 September 2017|archive-date= 1 September 2017|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170901032141/https://talksport.com/football/arsenal-fc-transfer-news-donyell-malen-returns-holland-join-psv-eindhoven-permanent-deal|url-status= live}}</ref>

Malen went on to play as a winger for [[Jong PSV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2017/10/20/netherlands/eerste-divisie/jong-psv/rkc-waalwijk/2463276/|title=Jong PSV vs RKC Waalwijk|publisher=Soccerway|access-date=21 February 2018|archive-date=31 July 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210731162954/https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2017/10/20/netherlands/eerste-divisie/jong-psv/rkc-waalwijk/2463276/|url-status=live}}</ref> On 24 November Malen scored a brace in Jong PSV's 6–0 win over [[SC Telstar|Telstar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ed.nl/psv/ook-psv-aanvaller-donyell-malen-gelooft-nu-in-het-ketchup-verhaal~a6687fac/|title=Ook PSV-aanvaller Donyell Malen gelooft nu in het ketchup-verhaal|language=nl|website=ED.nl|access-date=25 November 2017|archive-date=1 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201041952/https://www.ed.nl/psv/ook-psv-aanvaller-donyell-malen-gelooft-nu-in-het-ketchup-verhaal~a6687fac/|url-status=live}}</ref> He scored again in PSV II's 3–0 win over [[FC Oss]] on 27 November.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bd.nl/fc-oss/fc-oss-kansloos-onderuit-tegen-jong-psv~a68a3a60/|title=FC Oss kansloos onderuit tegen Jong PSV|language=nl|website=BD.nl}}</ref> Malen scored and picked up an assist in PSV II's 2–3 loss to [[Fortuna Sittard|Fortuna]] upon 4 December.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2017/12/04/netherlands/eerste-divisie/jong-psv/fortuna-sittard/2463342/|title=PSV II VS. FORTUNA SITTARD 2 – 3|publisher=Soccerway|access-date=21 February 2018|archive-date=1 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180901184022/https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2017/12/04/netherlands/eerste-divisie/jong-psv/fortuna-sittard/2463342/|url-status=live}}</ref>

He again scored in a 1–1 draw away to [[Go Ahead Eagles]] on 12 December.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2017/12/12/netherlands/eerste-divisie/stichting-go-ahead-eagles/jong-psv/2463345/|title=Go Ahead Eagles 1–1 PSV II|publisher=Soccerway}}</ref> Malen went on to be named in [[Voetbal International]]'s Jupiler League team of the week a day later.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vi.nl/nieuws/limburgse-glorie-in-het-elftal-van-de-week-|title=Limburgse glorie in het Elftal van de Week|language=nl|website=Voetbal International.com}}</ref>

Malen was awarded the Bronze Bull for being the Best Talent for the second period of the [[2017–18 Eerste Divisie|2017–18 Jupiler League]] on 29 January 2018.<ref name="Award" /><ref name="Award1">{{cite tweet|user=ESPNnl|number=958053414663016449|title= 🐂 Donyell Malen (Jong @PSV) krijgt de Bronzen Stier voor grootste talent van de tweede periode in de @jupilerleague uitgereikt van een trotse moeder|date=January 29, 2018}}</ref> He went to make his debut for [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]] in a 4–0 [[Eredivisie]] win over [[PEC Zwolle]] on 3 February.<ref name="Debut">{{cite web |date=3 February 2018 |title=Donyell Malen debuteert in het 'grote' PSV: 'In een vol stadion is toch anders' |url=https://www.omroepbrabant.nl/nieuws/2641342/donyell-malen-debuteert-in-het-grote-psv-in-een-vol-stadion-is-toch-anders |access-date=30 April 2018 |website=Omroep Brabant |language=nl}}</ref> Malen went on to win the [[2017–18 Eredivisie|2018 Eredivisie]] title with PSV.<ref name="PSV" /> He also ended the 2017–18 season as Jong PSV's topscorer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.omroepbrabant.nl/nieuws/2714084/balans-van-de-brabantse-jupiler-league-clubs-goalgetter-lieder-donkerrood-rkc-smaakmaker-kamaci|title=Balans van de Brabantse Jupiler League-clubs: goalgetter Lieder, donkerrood RKC, smaakmaker Kamaçi|language=nl|website=Omroep Brabant.nl|date=30 April 2018 }}</ref>

On 14 September 2019, Malen scored all five goals for PSV as they thrashed [[SBV Vitesse|Vitesse]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49704824|title=Donyell Malen: PSV Eindhoven youngster scores five in rout over Vitesse|date=14 September 2019|access-date=22 September 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> On 29 October 2020, he scored a brace in a 2–1 away win over [[AC Omonia|Omonia]] in the [[2020–21 UEFA Europa League]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/match/2029750--omonoia-vs-psv/ |title=Omonia 1–2 PSV |publisher=UEFA |date=29 October 2020 |access-date=29 October 2020 |archive-date=4 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220704055246/https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/match/2029750--omonoia-vs-psv/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Malen had his most productive campaign for PSV during the [[2020–21 PSV Eindhoven season|2020–21 season]], scoring 19 goals in 32 matches as his club finished second in the [[2020–21 Eredivisie|Eredivisie]].<ref name="Dortmundeal">{{cite web |last=Bosher |first=Luke |date=27 July 2021 |title=Borussia Dortmund sign forward Donyell Malen from PSV |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4204105/2021/07/25/borussia-dortmund-sign-forward-donyell-malen-from-psv/ |website=The Athletic |access-date=27 July 2021}}</ref> He added a further eight goals across Europa League and [[KNVB Cup]] competition and he also registered ten assists, displaying his characteristics as a multi-faceted forward.<ref name="Dortmundeal" />

===Borussia Dortmund===
On 27 July 2021, Malen completed a move to [[Bundesliga]] club [[Borussia Dortmund]], signing a five-year deal.<ref name="Dortmundeal" /> On 28 September 2021, he scored his first [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] goal in a 1–0 victory over [[Sporting CP]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/match/2032724/ |title=Dortmund 1–0 Sporting CP |publisher=UEFA |date=28 September 2021 }}</ref> In the [[2022–23 Borussia Dortmund season|2022–23 season]], he scored nine league goals, finishing as his club's joint top scorer alongside [[Julian Brandt]] and [[Sébastien Haller]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bvb.de/de/en/teams/football/player/donyell-malen.html |title=Donyell Malen |publisher=Borussia Dortmund }}</ref>

On 20 February 2024, he became the first Dutch footballer to score against a team from his country in the Champions League, since [[Arjen Robben]] in 2016, after doing so in a 1–1 draw against his former club PSV.<ref>{{cite web |last=Buxton |first=Richard |date=20 February 2024 |title=📸 Donyell Malen breaks 8️⃣ year cycle with goal against former club |url=https://onefootball.com/en/news/donyell-malen-breaks-8-year-cycle-with-goal-against-former-club-39080539 |access-date=15 June 2024 |website=OneFootball}}</ref> In the 2023–24 season, he set his personal best record in Bundesliga, becoming his club's top scorer in the league with 13 goals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/who-is-donyell-malen-borussia-dortmund-netherlands-forward-arsenal-ajax-youth-16679 |title=Donyell Malen: Who is Borussia Dortmund's flying Dutch forward? |publisher=Bundesliga |date=14 March 2024 }}</ref> In the same season, he featured in the [[2024 UEFA Champions League final|Champions League final]] as a substitute, where his club lost 2–0 to [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]].<ref name=":2">{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/story/_/id/40204974/uefa-champions-league-final-2024-live-updates-highlights-real-madrid-borussia-dortmund |title=Champions League final, as it happened: Real Madrid 2, Dortmund 0 |publisher=ESPN |date=1 June 2024 }}</ref>

===Aston Villa===
[[File:St. Louis City vs Aston Villa (Jul 2025) 13.jpg|thumb|Malen playing for [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in 2025]]
On 13 January 2025, 25-year-old Malen signed for [[Premier League]] club [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] for an undisclosed fee, reported to be £21m plus addons.<ref>{{cite web |date=14 January 2025 |title=Aston Villa announce Donyell Malen signing |url=https://www.avfc.co.uk/news/2025/january/14/villa-announce-donyell-malen-signing/ |access-date=14 January 2025 |website=Aston Villa Football Club}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Donyell Malen transfer: Aston Villa complete signing of Dutch forward from Borussia Dortmund |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/13288125/donyell-malen-transfer-aston-villa-complete-signing-of-dutch-forward-from-borussia-dortmund |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250114201319/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/13288125/donyell-malen-transfer-aston-villa-complete-signing-of-dutch-forward-from-borussia-dortmund |archive-date=14 January 2025 |access-date=17 January 2025 |work=Sky Sports |language=en-GB}}</ref> He made his debut for Villa on 26 January 2025 as a 65th-minute substitute for [[Leon Bailey]] against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Burnton |first=Simon |date=26 January 2025 |title=Aston Villa 1–1 West Ham United: Premier League – as it happened |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2025/jan/26/aston-villa-v-west-ham-united-premer-league-live-score-updates |access-date=26 January 2025 |work=[[The Guardian]] |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> On 2 April 2025, Malen scored his first Premier League goal in the 100th minute of a 3–0 away victory against [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Brighton v Aston Villa, 2024/25 |url=https://www.premierleague.com/match/116119 |access-date=2 April 2025 |publisher=Premier League}}</ref>

After scoring four goals and registering one assist in November 2025, fans voted Malen as Aston Villa's Player of the Month.<ref>{{Cite web |date=8 December 2025 |title=Donyell Malen crowned November Player of the Month |url=https://www.avfc.co.uk/news/2025/december/08/news-malen-crowned-november-player-of-the-month/ |access-date=8 December 2025 |website=Aston Villa Football Club}}</ref>

=== Roma ===
On 16 January 2026, Malen signed for [[AS Roma|Roma]] in an undisclosed deal.<ref>{{Cite web |date=16 January 2026 |title=Donyell Malen signs for Roma |url=https://www.asroma.com/en/news/74665/donyell-malen-signs-for-roma |access-date=16 January 2026 |website=www.asroma.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2026-01-16 |title=Donyell Malen joins Serie A side Roma |url=https://www.avfc.co.uk/news/2026/january/16/signing-malen-joins-serie-a-side-roma/ |access-date=2026-01-16 |website=Aston Villa Football Club}}</ref> It was reported that to be a loan with a fee of around €2m, with an obligation to buy for €25m at the end of the season.<ref>{{Cite news |last=McGrath |first=Mike |last2=Percy |first2=John |date=2026-01-14 |title=Aston Villa pave way for Tammy Abraham move with £25m Donyell Malen exit |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2026/01/14/aston-villa-pave-way-tammy-abraham-move-donyel-malen-exit/ |access-date=2026-01-16 |work=The Telegraph |language=en-GB |issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Malen made his Roma debut on 18 January 2026 in an away game against [[Torino FC|Torino]], where he also scored his first goal for the club.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2026-01-18 |title=Torino 0-2 Roma: Malen marks debut with goal as Dybala ends drought |url=https://www.fotmob.com/news/1mz3vk1yax4mu1w5oojjtmodsy-torino-0-2-roma-malen-marks-debut-goal-dybala-ends-drought |access-date=2026-02-10 |website=FotMob |language=en}}</ref> He scored his first brace for the club against [[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]] on 9 February 2026,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Roma vs Cagliari: Serie A stats & head-to-head |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c301gqmnnp3t |access-date=2026-02-10 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> and repeated the feat six days later against [[SSC Napoli|Napoli]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Napoli vs Roma: Serie A stats & head-to-head |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cj98jgg881jt |access-date=2026-02-25 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 10 April 2026, he scored a hat-trick against [[Pisa SC|Pisa]], becoming the first (and only) player to do so in the entire Serie A season.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Malen scores first Serie A hat-trick of the season |url=https://romapress.net/malen-scores-first-serie-a-hat-trick-of-the-season/ |access-date=2026-05-26 |website=RomaPress |language=en-GB}}</ref>

In May 2026, Roma made Malen's transfer permanent after securing qualification for European competition, activating the €25m obligation-to-buy clause in the deal agreed with Aston Villa.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2026-05-16 |title=Confirmed: Roma will make Malen’s deal permanent for €25 million |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/articles/confirmed-roma-malen-deal-permanent-211500980.html |access-date=2026-05-16 |website=Yahoo! Sports}}</ref> By then, Malen had established himself as Roma's leading scorer in [[2025–26 Serie A|Serie A]], netting 13 league goals during the second half of the 2025–26 campaign.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://onefootball.com/de/news/malen-completes-permanent-25m-roma-move-from-aston-villa-as-inter-win-coppa-italia-42862149 |title=Malen completes permanent 25m Roma move from Aston Villa as Inter win Coppa Italia |publisher=OneFootball |date=13 May 2026 }}</ref> He concluded the season with 14 goals, scoring his final goal in a 2–0 away victory over [[Hellas Verona FC|Hellas Verona]], securing his club's place in the [[2026–27 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]] for the first time in seven years.<ref>{{cite web |last=Campanale |first=Susy |url=https://football-italia.net/serie-a-verona-0-2-roma-malen-champions-league/ |title=Serie A {{!}} Verona 0-2 Roma: Malen guarantees Champions League |publisher=Football Italia |date=24 May 2026 }}</ref> On 25 May, Roma announced that Malen had signed a permanent deal running until 30 June 2030.<ref>{{cite web |title=Donyell Malen statement |url=https://www.asroma.com/en/news/75420/donyell-malen-statement |website=AS Roma |publisher=AS Roma |access-date=26 May 2026 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260526151202/https://www.asroma.com/en/news/75420/donyell-malen-statement |archive-date=26 May 2026 |date=26 May 2026}}</ref>

==International career ==
===Youth===
[[File:Austria U-18 vs. Netherlands U-18 2017-03-23 (081).jpg|thumb|180px|right|Malen in March 2017 while playing for the Netherlands]]
Born in the Netherlands, Malen is of Surinamese descent through his father.<ref name=":0">{{cite web |title=Profvoetballers van Surinaamse afkomst |url=https://www.natiosuriname.com/p/profvoetballers-van-surinaamse-afkomst.html |url-status=usurped |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200924084846/https://www.natiosuriname.com/p/profvoetballers-van-surinaamse-afkomst.html |archive-date=24 September 2020 |access-date=22 November 2020 |website=Natio Suriname &#124; Voetbal}}</ref> He has represented the Netherlands at every age group from [[Netherlands national under-15 football team|under-15]] to senior level. He was a member of the [[Netherlands national under-17 football team|Netherlands under-17 team]] that reached the semi-finals of the [[2016 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]] held in [[Azerbaijan]].<ref name="U17">{{cite web|title=Netherlands U17s defeated in Euro semi-final|url=http://www.football-oranje.com/netherlands-u17s-knocked-european-championships/|website=Football Oranje.com|date=18 May 2016 |access-date=16 March 2017|archive-date=24 December 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201224013721/http://www.football-oranje.com/netherlands-u17s-knocked-european-championships/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/under17/news/0252-0cda5f07bc4a-be8e9ee5f13b-1000/#chong+fore+netherlands+edge+sweden|title=Chong to the fore as Netherlands edge Sweden|publisher=[[UEFA]]|access-date=25 December 2021|archive-date=25 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211225052143/https://www.uefa.com/under17/news/0252-0cda5f07bc4a-be8e9ee5f13b-1000/#chong+fore+netherlands+edge+sweden|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="U17*">{{cite web|title=Portugal see off Netherlands in semi-finals|url=https://www.uefa.com/under17/match/2019911--portugal-vs-netherlands/|publisher=[[UEFA]]|access-date=16 March 2017|archive-date=16 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170616140838/http://www.uefa.com/under17/season=2016/matches/round=2000594/match=2019911/index.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Jong*>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-oranje.com/netherlands-u21s-beaten-austria-u18s-hammer-czech-republic/|title=Netherlands U21s beaten by Austria but U18s hammer Czech Republic|website=Football Oranje.com|date=27 March 2017 |access-date=29 March 2017|archive-date=13 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180713133253/http://www.football-oranje.com/netherlands-u21s-beaten-austria-u18s-hammer-czech-republic/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.uefa.com/under17/season=2016/matches/byround/index.html| title = 2016 UEFA Under 17 Euros – Matches| publisher = [[UEFA]]| access-date = 4 September 2016| archive-date = 14 September 2017| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170914014834/http://www.uefa.com/under17/season=2016/matches/byround/index.html| url-status = dead}}</ref><ref name="Showtime">{{cite web |title=Dutch U19 Squad |url=https://www.ajaxshowtime.com/article/bijzaken-en-geruchten/100985/acht-ajacieden-bij-oefenstage-oranje-u19#SOLEdZJRmqu079Rv.97 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220090354/https://www.ajaxshowtime.com/article/bijzaken-en-geruchten/100985/acht-ajacieden-bij-oefenstage-oranje-u19#SOLEdZJRmqu079Rv.97 |archive-date=20 December 2016 |website=Ajax Showtime.com}}</ref>

===Senior===
The 20-year-old Malen made his senior international debut for the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] on 6 September 2019, in a [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying Group C|UEFA Euro 2020 qualifier]] against [[Germany national football team|Germany]] in Hamburg. He came off the bench in the 58th minute and scored his team's third goal in a 4–2 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/match/2026177--germany-vs-netherlands/|title=Germany 2–4 Netherlands|publisher=[[UEFA]]|date=6 September 2019|access-date=6 September 2019|archive-date=5 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605011833/https://www.uefa.com/european-qualifiers/season=2020/matches/round=2001086/match=2026177/|url-status=live}}</ref>

Malen was a member of the Netherlands squad for [[UEFA Euro 2020]] and made his first tournament appearance as an 89th minute substitute in their [[UEFA Euro 2020 Group B|Group B]] opener against [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]] on 13 June 2021.<ref>{{cite news |title=Netherlands 3–2 Ukraine – Denzel Dumfries grabs late winner to spare Dutch blushes in group C at Euro 2020 |url=https://www.eurosport.co.uk/football/euro-2020/2021/euro-2020-news-netherlands-v-ukraine-follow-the-amsterdam-arena-affair-live_sto8361622/story.shtml |website=eurosport.co.uk |date=13 June 2021 |access-date=8 January 2023}}</ref> He made another appearance from the bench in the second match, assisting [[Denzel Dumfries]]' second goal as the Dutch beat [[Austria national football team|Austria]] to ensure their progress to the knockout rounds.<ref>{{cite web |title=Netherlands v Austria Euro 2020 Live |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2021/jun/17/netherlands-v-austria-euro-2020-live |website=The Guardian |access-date=13 June 2024 |date=18 June 2021}}</ref> He was selected to start in the team's final group match against [[North Macedonia national football team|North Macedonia]] and assisted [[Memphis Depay]]'s opening goal of the 3–0 win.<ref>{{cite web |title=North Macedonia 0–3 Netherlands: Oranje shine on Pandev's farewell |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/history/news/026a-12931090d267-a6ee38ed7f2e-1000--north-macedonia-0-3-netherlands-oranje-shine-on-pandev-s-far/ |publisher=[[UEFA]] |access-date=13 June 2024}}</ref> Malen retained his place in the starting line-up for the [[UEFA Euro 2020 knockout stage#Round of 16|round of 16]] match with [[Czech Republic national football team|Czechia]] but was substituted after 57 minutes as the Netherlands were beaten 2–0 and eliminated from the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |last=Sanders |first=Emma |date=26 June 2021 |title=Netherlands 0–2 Czech Republic: Tomas Holes and Patrik Schick goals shock Dutch |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51198518 |access-date=13 June 2024 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

Malen scored three goals during [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification]] but was omitted from the [[2022 FIFA World Cup squads#Group A#Netherlands|26-man squad]] for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup|tournament finals]] in Qatar.<ref>{{cite web |title=Depay, Klaassen in Dutch squad; Gravenberch, Danjuma miss out |url=https://www.fifa.com/en/articles/depay-klaassen-in-dutch-squad-gravenberch-danjuma-miss-out |publisher=FIFA |access-date=13 June 2024 |date=11 November 2022}}</ref>

In June 2023, Malen was part of the Netherlands' squad for the [[2023 UEFA Nations League Finals]]. He scored the opening goal of an eventual 4–2 loss to [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] in the semi-final and also started the third place play-off loss to [[Italy national football team|Italy]], where he was substituted at half time for [[Steven Bergwijn]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefanationsleague/match/2035581--netherlands-vs-croatia/|title=Netherlands vs Croatia|date=15 June 2023|access-date=7 June 2024|publisher=UEFA}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefanationsleague/match/2035583--netherlands-vs-italy/|title=Netherlands vs Italy|date=18 June 2023|access-date=7 June 2024|publisher=UEFA}}</ref>

On 29 May 2024, Malen was named in the Netherlands' squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Callum |date=29 May 2024 |title=Netherlands Euro 2024 squad: Georginio Wijnaldum and Daley Blind retained |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5526712/2024/05/29/netherlands-euro-2024-squad-confirmed/ |access-date=7 June 2024 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In the round of 16 match against [[Romania national football team|Romania]], he scored a brace in a 3–0 victory, securing his country's qualification to the quarter-finals.<ref>{{cite web |title=Netherlands 3–0 Romania (Jul 2, 2024) Game Analysis |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report/_/gameId/703937 |date=2 July 2024 |access-date=2 July 2024 |publisher=ESPN}}</ref>

==Style of play==
Malen combines dribbling skills and a natural instinct for goal scoring. He has been likened by ex-Ajax youth coach [[Brian Tevreden (footballer born 1981)|Brian Tevreden]] to Chilean forward [[Alexis Sánchez]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Ex-Ajax chief says Arsenal whizkid Donyell Malen just like Alexis Sanchez |url=http://ghanasoccernet.com/ex-ajax-chief-says-arsenal-whizkid-donyell-malen-just-like-alexis-sanchez |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170412224711/http://ghanasoccernet.com/ex-ajax-chief-says-arsenal-whizkid-donyell-malen-just-like-alexis-sanchez |archive-date=12 April 2017 |access-date=12 April 2017 |website=Ghana Soccernet.com}}</ref>

== Personal life ==
Born in [[Wieringen]], [[Hollands Kroon]], Malen is of Surinamese descent through his father.<ref name=":0" /> Malen's mother separated from his father at a young age and he was later raised by his mother and grandparents. Malen's mother re-married when he was seven, and he then lived with his new step-father alongside his four new half-brothers and sisters.<ref name=":1">{{cite web |date=10 April 2020 |title='They used to affectionately call Donyell Malen boeroe' |url=https://www.psv.nl/en/media/artikel/vroeger-al-noemden-ze-donyell-malen-liefkozend-boeroe |access-date=15 January 2025 |website=psv.nl}}</ref> Malen recognised his grandmother as the person who most encouraged him to become a footballer, teaching him how to kick a ball when he was three years old.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-01-15 |title=Getting to know Donyell Malen |url=https://www.avfc.co.uk/news/2025/january/15/getting-to-know-donyell-malen/ |access-date=2025-01-15 |website=Aston Villa Football Club}}</ref> Nicknamed "Don" by his friends and family, right after his first goal with Roma he has been renamed 'Bobby Malen' by fans, because of his surname's loose assonance to [[Bob Marley]]'s.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2026-05-27 |title=Malen, la storia del soprannome Bobby: ecco come nasce |url=https://www.forzaroma.info/news-as-roma/malen-la-storia-del-soprannome-bobby-ecco-come-nasce/ |access-date=2026-05-29 |website=Forzaroma.info |language=it}}</ref> The player has shown appreciation for his new nickname, and the club used it in the video announcing the signing of his permanent deal.<ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cQ5MTMCWl4s |title=Malen resta alla Roma, l’annuncio: «Bobby resta». Nel video social anche "Il Messaggero" |date=2026-05-26 |last=Il Messaggero |access-date=2026-05-29 |via=YouTube}}</ref>

Malen was a childhood friend of future Netherlands teammate [[Matthijs de Ligt]].<ref name=":1" />

